# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fish-shell
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line interface** (**CLI**), also known as a **command-line shell**, is a means of interacting with software via commands – each formatted as a line of text.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The concept of interacting with a computer via text evolved over two decades, transitioning from physical hardware to sophisticated software.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Before the CLI, computers were programmed using physical switches or punched cards.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The shift toward a "command" style interaction began with the use of Teleprinters (Teletypes).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Early systems like the Whirlwind I (1951) at MIT began utilizing typewriter-like inputs for direct control, moving away from batch processing where you'd hand a stack of cards to an operator and wait hours for a result.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Devices like the Teletype Model 33, introduced in 1963, allowed operators to type a command and receive a printed response from the computer.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The **command-line interpreter** emerged when computers became powerful enough to handle multiple users at once, known as Time-Sharing.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), developed in 1961 at MIT, introduced the first true command-line interpreter.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] For the first time, a user could type a command like LOGIN or PRINT, and a dedicated program (the supervisor) would parse that text and execute the corresponding function.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, Louis Pouzin introduced the software we now recognize as a "shell" for the Multics operating system, providing a programmable environment for executing scripts.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Many operating system and software development utilities provide CLI.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI enables automating programs since commands can be stored in a script file that can be used repeatedly.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A script allows its contained commands to be executed as a group (as a single program).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Alternatives to a CLI include a GUI (including the desktop metaphor such as Windows), text-based menuing (including DOS Shell and IBM AIX SMIT), and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Compared with a graphical user interface, a command-line interface requires fewer system resources to implement.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Since options to commands are given in a few characters in each command line, an experienced user often finds the options easier to access.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Automation of repetitive tasks is simplified by line editing and history mechanisms for storing frequently used sequences; this may extend to a scripting language that can take parameters and variable options.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line history can be kept, allowing review or repetition of commands.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line system may require paper or online manuals for the user's reference, although often a *help* option provides a concise review of the options of a command.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line environment may not provide graphical enhancements such as different fonts or extended edit windows found in a GUI.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] It may be difficult for a new user to become familiar with all the commands and options available, compared with the icons and drop-down menus of a graphical user interface, without reference to manuals.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Operating system (OS) command-line interfaces are usually distinct programs supplied with the operating system.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A program that implements such a text interface is often called a command-line interpreter, command processor, or shell.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Under most operating systems, it is possible to replace the default shell program with alternatives; examples include 4DOS for DOS, 4OS2 for OS/2, and 4NT / Take Command for Windows.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] For example, the default Windows GUI is a shell GUI named EXPLORER.EXE, as defined in the SHELL=EXPLORER.EXE line in the WIN.INI configuration file.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] This program strictly speaking is a shell GUI and by extension a shell (strictly speaking, the Windows shell is shell32.dll not explorer.exe which is a shell GUI for shell32.dll), but it is not a CLI (command-line interpreter) nor a shell CLI (shell command-line interface).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Application programs (as opposed to operating systems) may also have command-line interfaces.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Some applications support a CLI, presenting their own prompt to the user and accepting command lines.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Other programs support both a CLI and a GUI.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, a GUI is simply a wrapper around a separate CLI executable file.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, a program may provide a CLI as an optional alternative to its GUI.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs and GUIs often support different functionality.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] For example, all features of MATLAB, a numerical analysis computer program, are available via the CLI, whereas the MATLAB GUI exposes only a subset of features.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In Colossal Cave Adventure from 1975, the user uses a CLI to enter one or two words to explore a cave system.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line interface evolved from a form of communication conducted by people over teleprinter (TTY) machines.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Sometimes these involved sending an order or a confirmation using telex.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Early computer systems often used a teleprinter to interact with an operator.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The mechanical teleprinter was replaced by a "glass tty", a keyboard and screen emulating the teleprinter.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] "Smart" terminals permitted additional functions, such as cursor movement over the entire screen, or local editing of data on the terminal for transmission to the computer.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] As the microcomputer revolution replaced the traditional – minicomputer + terminals – time sharing architecture, hardware terminals were replaced by terminal emulators — PC software that interpreted terminal signals sent through the PC's serial ports.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] These were typically used to interface an organization's new PC's with their existing mini- or mainframe computers, or to connect PC to PC.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Some of these PCs were running Bulletin Board System software.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Early operating system CLIs were implemented as part of resident monitor programs, and could not easily be replaced.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The first implementation of the shell as a replaceable component was part of the Multics time-sharing operating system.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, MIT Computation Center staff member Louis Pouzin developed the RUNCOM tool for executing command scripts while allowing argument substitution.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin coined the term *shell* to describe the technique of using commands like a programming language, and wrote a paper about how to implement the idea in the Multics operating system.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin returned to his native France in 1965, and the first Multics shell was developed by Glenda Schroeder.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The first Unix shell, the V6 shell, was developed by Ken Thompson in 1971 at Bell Labs and was modeled after Schroeder's Multics shell.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell was introduced in 1977 as a replacement for the V6 shell.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Although it is used as an interactive command interpreter, it was also intended as a scripting language and contains most of the features that are commonly considered to produce structured programs.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell led to the development of the KornShell (ksh), Almquist shell (ash), and the popular Bourne-again shell (or Bash).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Early microcomputers themselves were based on a command-line interface such as CP/M, DOS or AppleSoft BASIC.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] During the 1980s and 1990s, the introduction of the Apple Macintosh and of Microsoft Windows on PCs saw the command line interface as the primary user interface replaced by the Graphical User Interface.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The command line remained available as an alternative user interface, often used by system administrators and other advanced users for system administration, computer programming and batch processing.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In November 2006, Microsoft released version 1.0 of Windows PowerShell (formerly codenamed *Monad*), which combined features of traditional Unix shells with their proprietary object-oriented .NET Framework.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] MinGW and Cygwin are open-source packages for Windows that offer a Unix-like CLI.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Microsoft provides MKS Inc.'s ksh implementation *MKS Korn shell* for Windows through their Services for UNIX add-on.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Since 2001, the Macintosh operating system macOS has been based on a Unix-like operating system called Darwin.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] On these computers, users can access a Unix-like command-line interface by running the terminal emulator program called Terminal, which is found in the Utilities sub-folder of the Applications folder, or by remotely logging into the machine using ssh.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Z shell is the default shell for macOS; Bash, tcsh, and the KornShell are also provided.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Before macOS Catalina, Bash was the default.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI is used whenever a large vocabulary of commands or queries, coupled with a wide (or arbitrary) range of options, can be entered more rapidly as text than with a pure GUI.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] This is typically the case with operating system command shells.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also used by systems with insufficient resources to support a graphical user interface.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Some computer language systems (such as Python, Forth, LISP, Rexx, and many dialects of BASIC) provide an interactive command-line mode to allow for rapid evaluation of code.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are often used by programmers and system administrators, in engineering and scientific environments, and by technically advanced personal computer users.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also popular among people with visual disabilities since the commands and responses can be displayed using refreshable Braille displays.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] *External* commands run executables found in separate executable files.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The command line interpreter searches for executable files with names matching the external command.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In this format, the delimiters between command-line elements are whitespace characters and the end-of-line delimiter is the newline delimiter.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] This is a widely used (but not universal) convention.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line interface can generally be considered as consisting of syntax and semantics.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The *syntax* is the grammar that all commands must follow.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of operating systems, DOS and Unix each define their own set of rules that all commands must follow.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of embedded systems, each vendor, such as Nortel, Juniper Networks or Cisco Systems, defines their own proprietary set of rules.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] These rules also dictate how a user navigates through the system of commands.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The *semantics* define what sort of operations are possible, on what sort of data these operations can be performed, and how the grammar represents these operations and data—the symbolic meaning in the syntax.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Two different CLIs may agree on either syntax or semantics, but it is only when they agree on both that they can be considered sufficiently similar to allow users to use both CLIs without needing to learn anything, as well as to enable re-use of scripts.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A simple CLI will display a prompt, accept a *command line* typed by the user terminated by the Enter key, then execute the specified command and provide textual display of results or error messages.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Advanced CLIs will validate, interpret and parameter-expand the command line before executing the specified command, and optionally capture or redirect its output.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Unlike a button or menu item in a GUI, a command line is typically self-documenting, stating exactly what the user wants done.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In addition, command lines usually include many defaults that can be changed to customize the results.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] These advantages mean that a user must figure out a complex command or series of commands only once, because they can be saved, to be used again.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] where *doSomething* is, in effect, a verb, *how* an adverb (for example, should the command be executed *verbosely* or *quietly*) and *toFiles* an object or objects (typically one or more files) on which the command should act.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The `>` in the third example is a redirection operator, telling the command-line interpreter to send the output of the command not to its own standard output (the screen) but to the named file.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Using `>>` will redirect the output and append it to the file.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Another redirection operator is the vertical bar (`|`), which creates a pipeline where the output of one command becomes the input to the next command.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, such as Unix-like systems or Windows, one can modify the set of available commands by modifying which paths appear in the PATH environment variable or its equivalent.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] On Unix-like systems, the file containing the executable or script for a command also needs to be given execute permission.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The directories in the path variable are searched in the order they are given.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] By re-ordering the path, one can run e.g.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] `\OS2\MDOS\E.EXE` instead of `\OS2\E.EXE`, when the default is the opposite.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Renaming of the executables also works: people often rename their favourite editor to EDIT, for example.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The command line allows one to restrict available commands, such as access to advanced internal commands.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The Windows CMD.EXE also supports restricting available commands.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Often, shareware programs will limit the range of commands, including printing a command 'your administrator has disabled running batch files' from the prompt.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Some CLIs, such as those in network routers, have a hierarchy of modes, with a different set of commands supported in each mode.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The set of commands are grouped by association with security, system, interface, etc.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In these systems the user might traverse through a series of sub-modes.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] For example, if the CLI had two modes called *interface* and *system*, the user might use the command *interface* to enter the interface mode.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] At this point, commands from the system mode may not be accessible until the user exits the interface mode and enters the system mode.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's flagship MVS operating systems, the *Authorised Program Facility* (*APF*) allows certain *authorized programs* to run with enhanced privileges, analogous to UID(0) in Unix-like systems.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] TSO/E supports calling, e.g., authorized commands, but only for those commands, programs and services in an installation controlled list.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A command prompt (or just *prompt*) is a sequence of (one or more) characters used in a command-line interface to indicate readiness to accept commands.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] It literally prompts the user to take action.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A prompt usually ends with one of the characters `$`, `%`, `#`, `:`, `>` or `-` and often includes other information, such as the path of the current working directory and the hostname.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] On many Unix and derivative systems, the prompt commonly ends in `$` or `%` if the user is a normal user, but in `#` if the user is a superuser ("root" in Unix terminology).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, special tokens in the definition of the prompt can be used to cause external programs to be called by the command-line interpreter while displaying the prompt.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS' COMMAND.COM and in Windows NT's cmd.exe users can modify the prompt by issuing a `PROMPT` command or by directly changing the value of the corresponding `%PROMPT%` environment variable.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The default of most modern systems, the `C:\>` style is obtained, for instance, with `PROMPT $P$G`.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The default of older DOS systems, `C>` is obtained by just `PROMPT`, although on some systems this produces the newer `C:\>` style, unless used on floppy drives A: or B:; on those systems `PROMPT $N$G` can be used to override the automatic default and explicitly switch to the older style.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Many Unix systems feature the `$PS1` variable (Prompt String 1), although other variables also may affect the prompt (depending on the shell used).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In zsh the `$RPROMPT` variable controls an optional *prompt* on the right-hand side of the display.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] It is not a real prompt in that the location of text entry does not change.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] It is used to display information on the same line as the prompt, but right-justified.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In RISC OS the command prompt is a `*` symbol, and thus (OS) CLI commands are often referred to as *star commands*.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] One can also access the same commands from other command lines (such as the BBC BASIC command line), by preceding the command with a `*`.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's TSO, the command prompt is referred to as the READY prompt, after the word `READY` in the prompt.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Some shells, such as Bash, zsh, and PowerShell, allow the use of prompt systems that display a lot more information in the command prompt, like the type of remote connection, the state of machine sensors, or additional information about a version control system.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] They often use several ANSI colors, Unicode characters, and advanced shell features to set up a colorful display.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line argument** or **parameter** is an item of information provided to a program when it is started.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A program can have many command-line arguments that identify sources or destinations of information, or that alter the operation of the program.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] When a command processor is active a program is typically invoked by typing its name followed by command-line arguments (if any).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] `file.s` is a command-line argument which tells the program rm to remove the file named `file.s`.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Some programming languages, such as C, C++ and Java, allow a program to interpret the command-line arguments by handling them as string parameters in the main function.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Other languages, such as Python, expose operating system specific API (functionality) through the `sys` module, and in particular `sys.argv` for *command-line arguments*.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like operating systems, a single hyphen used in place of a file name is a special value specifying that a program should handle data coming from the standard input or send data to the standard output.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line option** or simply **option** (also known as a **flag** or **switch**) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Options follow the command name on the command line, separated by, e.g., commas, spaces.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Separators are not always required, such as `Dir/?` and `DIR /?` in DOS, which have the same effect of listing the DIR command's available options, whereas `dir --help` (in many versions of Unix) *does* require the option to be preceded by at least one space (and is case-sensitive).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The format of options varies widely between operating systems.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line argument parsing is used to parse the arguments of a program, and such functionality is offered in various languages.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] For example, getopt() is in the C POSIX library for parsing arguments.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In Multics, command-line options and subsystem keywords may be abbreviated.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] This idea appears to derive from the PL/I programming language, with its shortened keywords (e.g., STRG for STRINGRANGE and DCL for DECLARE).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] For example, in the Multics *forum* subsystem, the *-long_subject* parameter can be abbreviated *-lgsj*.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] It is also common for Multics commands to be abbreviated, typically corresponding to the initial letters of the words that are strung together with underscores to form command names, such as the use of *did* for *delete_iacl_dir*.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In some other systems abbreviations are automatic, such as permitting enough of the first characters of a command name to uniquely identify it (such as `SU` as an abbreviation for `SUPERUSER`) while others may have some specific abbreviations pre-programmed (e.g.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] `MD` for `MKDIR` in COMMAND.COM) or user-defined via batch scripts and aliases (e.g.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] On DOS, OS/2 and Windows, different programs called from their COMMAND.COM or CMD.EXE (or internal their commands) may use different syntax within the same operating system.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows, the forward slash (`/`) is most prevalent, although the hyphen-minus is also sometimes used.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In some of these systems (MS-DOS/PC DOS 2.xx, DOS Plus 2.1, DR-DOS 7.02 and higher, PTS-DOS, Embedded DOS, FreeDOS and RxDOS), the setting can also be pre-configured by a SWITCHAR directive in CONFIG.SYS.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] General Software's Embedded DOS provides a SWITCH command for the same purpose, whereas 4DOS allows the setting to be changed via `SETDOS /W:n`.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Also, the current setting is reflected also in the built-in help screens.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Some versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also support a PROMPT token `$/` to display the current setting.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] COMMAND.COM since DR-DOS 7.02 also provides a pseudo-environment variable named `%/%` to allow portable batchjobs to be written.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Several external DR-DOS commands additionally support an environment variable `%SWITCHAR%` to override the system setting.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] However, many programs are hardwired to use `/` only, rather than retrieving the switch setting before parsing command-line arguments.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like systems, the ASCII hyphen-minus begins options; the new (and GNU) convention is to use *two* hyphens then a word (e.g.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Two hyphen-minus characters without following letters (`--`) may indicate that the remaining arguments should not be treated as options, which is useful for example if a file name itself begins with a hyphen, or if further arguments are meant for an inner command (e.g., sudo).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Double hyphen-minuses are also sometimes used to prefix *long options* where more descriptive option names are used.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] This is a common feature of GNU software.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The *getopt* function and program, and the *getopts* command are usually used for parsing command-line options.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Unix command names, arguments and options are case-sensitive (except in a few examples, mainly where popular commands from other operating systems have been ported to Unix).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Conversational Monitor System (CMS) uses a single left parenthesis to separate options at the end of the command from the other arguments.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] OS/360 operator commands use a comma separated list of positional and keyword parameters; only documented command and keyword abbreviations are valid.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Keyword values are separated from the keywords with equal signs.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] TSO commands use a space separated list of positional and keyword parameters; keywords may be truncated to any unique sub-string.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Only documented command abbreviations are valid.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] One of the criticisms of a CLI is the lack of cues to the user as to the available actions.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In contrast, GUIs usually inform the user of available actions with menus, icons, or other visual cues.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] To overcome this limitation, many CLI programs display a usage message, typically when invoked with no arguments or one of `?`, `-?`, `-h`, `-H`, `/?`, `/h`, `/H`, `/Help`, `-help`, or `--help`.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] However, entering a program name without parameters in the hope that it will display usage help can be hazardous, as programs and scripts for which command line arguments are optional will execute without further notice.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Although desirable at least for the help parameter, programs may not support all option lead-in characters exemplified above.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Under DOS, where the default command-line option character can be changed from `/` to `-`, programs may query the SwitChar API in order to determine the current setting.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] So, if a program is not hardwired to support them all, a user may need to know the current setting even to be able to reliably request help.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] If the SwitChar has been changed to `-` and therefore the `/` character is accepted as an alternative path delimiter at the DOS command line, programs might misinterpret options like `/h` or `/H` as paths rather than help parameters.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] However, if given as the first or only parameter, most DOS programs will, by convention, accept it as a request for help regardless of the current SwitChar setting.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, different levels of help can be selected for a program.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Some programs supporting this allow to give a verbosity level as an optional argument to the help parameter (as in `/H:1`, `/H:2`, etc.) or they give just a short help on help parameters with question mark and a longer help screen for the other help options.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Depending on the program, additional or more specific help on accepted parameters is sometimes available by either providing the parameter in question as an argument to the help parameter or vice versa (as in `/H:W` or in `/W:?` (assuming `/W` would be another parameter supported by the program)).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In a similar fashion to the help parameter, but much less common, some programs provide additional information about themselves (like mode, status, version, author, license or contact information) when invoked with an *about* parameter like `-!`, `/!`, `-about`, or `--about`.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Since the `?` and `!` characters typically also serve other purposes at the command line, they may not be available in all scenarios, therefore, they should not be the only options to access the corresponding help information.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] If more detailed help is necessary than provided by a program's built-in internal help, many systems support a dedicated external `help *command*`" command (or similar), which accepts a command name as calling parameter and will invoke an external help system.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In addition to this, some newer versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also accept a `?%` command to display a list of available built-in pseudo-environment variables.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Besides their purpose as quick help reference this can be used in batchjobs to query the facilities of the underlying command-line processor.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Notice that these characters have different meanings than when used directly in the shell.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Angle brackets may be omitted when confusing the parameter name with a literal string is not likely.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In many areas of computing, but particularly in the command line, the space character can cause problems as it has two distinct and incompatible functions: as part of a command or parameter, or as a parameter or name separator.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Unix-based operating systems minimize the use of embedded spaces to minimize the need for quotes.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In Microsoft Windows, one often has to use quotes because embedded spaces (such as in directory names) are common.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The term **command-line interpreter** is applied to computer programs designed to interpret a sequence of lines of text which may be entered by a user, read from a file or another kind of data stream.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The context of interpretation is usually one of a given operating system or programming language.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line interpreters allow users to issue various commands in a very efficient (and often terse) way.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] This requires the user to know the names of the commands and their parameters, and the syntax of the language that is interpreted.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The Unix `#!` mechanism and OS/2 EXTPROC command facilitate the passing of batch files to external processors.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] One can use these mechanisms to write specific command processors for dedicated uses, and process external data files which reside in batch files.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Many graphical interfaces, such as the OS/2 Presentation Manager and early versions of Microsoft Windows use command lines to call helper programs to open documents and programs.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The commands are stored in the graphical shell or in files like the registry or the OS/2 `OS2USER.INI` file.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The earliest computers did not support interactive input/output devices, often relying on sense switches and lights to communicate with the computer operator.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] This was adequate for batch systems that ran one program at a time, often with the programmer acting as operator.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] This also had the advantage of low overhead, since lights and switches could be tested and set with one machine instruction.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Later a single system console was added to allow the operator to communicate with the system.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] From the 1960s onwards, user interaction with computers was primarily by means of command-line interfaces, initially on machines like the Teletype Model 33 ASR, but then on early CRT-based computer terminals such as the VT52.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] All of these devices were purely text based, with no ability to display graphics or pictures.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] For business application programs, text-based menus were used, but for more general interaction the command line was the interface.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Around 1964 Louis Pouzin introduced the concept and the name *shell* in Multics, building on earlier, simpler facilities in the Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS).
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] From the early 1970s the Unix operating system adapted the concept of a powerful command-line environment, and introduced the ability to *pipe* the output of one command in as input to another.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Unix also had the capability to save and re-run strings of commands as shell scripts which acted like custom commands.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was also the main interface for the early home computers such as the Commodore PET, Apple II and BBC Micro – almost always in the form of a BASIC interpreter.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] When more powerful business-oriented microcomputers arrived with CP/M and later DOS computers such as the IBM PC, the command line began to borrow some of the syntax and features of the Unix shells such as globbing and piping of output.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was first seriously challenged by the PARC GUI approach used in the 1983 Apple Lisa and the 1984 Apple Macintosh.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] A few computer users used GUIs such as GEOS and Windows 3.1 but the majority of IBM PC users did not replace their COMMAND.COM shell with a GUI until Windows 95 was released in 1995.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Most command-line interpreters support scripting, to various extents.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] They are, after all, interpreters of an interpreted programming language, albeit in many cases the language is unique to the particular command-line interpreter.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] They will interpret scripts, variously termed shell scripts or batch files, written in the language that they interpret.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Some command-line interpreters also incorporate the interpreter engines of other languages, such as REXX, in addition to their own, allowing the executing of scripts, in those languages, directly within the command-line interpreter itself.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] Conversely, scripting programming languages, in particular those with an eval function (such as REXX, Perl, Python, Ruby or Jython), can be used to implement command-line interpreters and filters.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] For a few operating systems, most notably DOS, such a command interpreter provides a more flexible command-line interface than the one supplied.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, such a command interpreter can present a highly customised user interface employing the user interface and input/output facilities of the language.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] The command line provides an interface between programs as well as the user.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] In this sense, a command line is an alternative to a dialog box.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] Editors and databases present a command line, in which alternate command processors might run.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] On the other hand, one might have options on the command line, which opens a dialog box.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] The latest version of 'Take Command' has this feature.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] DBase used a dialog box to construct command lines, which could be further edited before use.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like BASIC, diskpart, Edlin, and QBASIC all provide command-line interfaces, some of which use the system shell.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] Basic is modeled on the default interface for 8-bit Intel computers.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] Calculators can be run as command-line or dialog interfaces.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] Emacs provides a command-line interface in the form of its minibuffer.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] Commands and arguments can be entered using Emacs standard text editing support, and output is displayed in another buffer.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] There are a number of text mode games, like *Adventure* or *King's Quest 1-3*, which relied on the user typing commands at the bottom of the screen.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] One controls the character by typing commands like 'get ring' or 'look'.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] The program returns a text which describes how the character sees it, or makes the action happen.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] The text adventure *The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy*, a piece of interactive fiction based on Douglas Adams's book of the same name, is a teletype-style command-line game.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] The most notable of these interfaces is the standard streams interface, which allows the output of one command to be passed to the input of another.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] Text files can serve either purpose as well.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] This provides the interfaces of piping, filters and redirection.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] Under Unix, devices are files too, so the normal type of file for the shell used for stdin, stdout and stderr is a tty device file.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] Another command-line interface allows a shell program to launch helper programs, either to launch documents or start a program.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] The command is processed internally by the shell, and then passed on to another program to launch the document.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] The graphical interface of Windows and OS/2 rely heavily on command lines passed through to other programs – console or graphical, which then usually process the command line without presenting a user-console.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like the OS/2 E editor and some other IBM editors, can process command lines normally meant for the shell, the output being placed directly in the document window.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] A web browser's URL input field can be used as a command line.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] It can be used to *launch* web apps, access browser configuration, as well as perform a search.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] Google, which has been called "the command line of the internet" will perform a domain-specific search when it detects search parameters in a known format.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] This functionality is present whether the search is triggered from a browser field or on Google's website.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] There are JavaScript libraries that help developers write command line applications for the browser as standalone Web apps or as part of bigger applications.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] An example of such a website is the CLI interface to DuckDuckGo.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] There are also web-based SSH applications that allow access to a server’s command-line interface from a browser.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] Many PC video games feature a command line interface often referred to as a console.
[src:fish-shell/command-line-interface-p02] It is typically used by the game developers during development and by mod developers for debugging purposes as well as for cheating or skipping parts of the game.
[src:fish-shell/friendly-interactive-shell] fish displays incremental suggestions as the user types, based on command history and the current directory.
[src:fish-shell/friendly-interactive-shell] Command-specific completions, including options with descriptions, can be to some extent generated from the commands' man pages, but custom completions can also be included with software or written by users of the shell.
[src:fish-shell/friendly-interactive-shell] The creator of fish preferred to add new features as commands rather than syntax.
[src:fish-shell/friendly-interactive-shell] This made features more discoverable, as the built-in features allow searching commands with options and help texts.
[src:fish-shell/friendly-interactive-shell] Functions can also include human readable descriptions.
[src:fish-shell/friendly-interactive-shell] A special *help* command gives access to all the fish documentation in the user's web browser.
[src:fish-shell/friendly-interactive-shell] Some language constructs, like pipelines, functions and loops, have been implemented using so called subshells in other shell languages.
[src:fish-shell/friendly-interactive-shell] Subshells are child programs that run a few commands to perform a task, then exit back to the parent shell.
[src:fish-shell/friendly-interactive-shell] This implementation detail typically has the side effect that any state changes made in the subshell, such as variable assignments, do not propagate to the main shell. fish never creates subshells for language features; all builtins happen within the parent shell.
[src:fish-shell/friendly-interactive-shell] This Bash example doesn't do what it seems: because the loop body is a subshell, the update to `$found` is not persistent.
[src:fish-shell/friendly-interactive-shell] fish has a feature known as universal variables, which allows a user to permanently assign a value to a variable across all the user's running fish shells.
[src:fish-shell/friendly-interactive-shell] The variable value is remembered across logouts and reboots, and updates are immediately propagated to all running shells.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] This is the documentation for **fish**, the **f**riendly **i**nteractive **sh**ell.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] A shell is a program that helps you operate your computer by starting other programs. fish offers a command-line interface focused on usability and interactive use.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] This page explains how to install and set up fish and where to get more information.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] If this is your first time using fish, see the tutorial.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] If you are already familiar with other shells like bash and want to see the scripting differences, see Fish For Bash Users.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] For an overview of fish’s scripting language, see The Fish Language.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] If it would be useful in a script file, it’s here.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] For information on using fish interactively, see Interactive use.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] If it’s about key presses, syntax highlighting or anything else that needs an interactive terminal session, look here.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] If you need to install fish first, read on, the rest of this document will tell you how to get, install and configure fish.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] This section describes how to install, uninstall, start, and exit **fish**.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] It also explains how to make fish the default shell.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] Up-to-date instructions for installing the latest version of fish are on the fish homepage.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] To install the development version of fish, see the instructions on the project’s GitHub page.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] Once fish has been installed, open a terminal.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] There are multiple ways to switch to fish (or any other shell) as your default.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] The simplest method is to set your terminal emulator (e.g.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] GNOME Terminal, Apple’s Terminal.app, or Konsole) to start fish directly.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] See its configuration and set the program to start to `/usr/local/bin/fish` (the exact path depends on how you installed fish).
[src:fish-shell/index-page] Alternatively, you can set fish as your login shell so that it will be started by all terminal logins, including SSH.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] Setting fish as your login shell may cause issues, such as an incorrect `PATH`.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] Some operating systems, including a number of Linux distributions, require the login shell to be Bourne-compatible and to read configuration from `/etc/profile`. fish may not be suitable as a login shell on these systems.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] To change it back to another shell, substitute `fish` with `bash`, `tcsh` or `zsh` as appropriate in the above command.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] For uninstalling fish: see FAQ: Uninstalling fish.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] Because shell scripts are written in many different languages, they need to carry information about which interpreter should be used to execute them.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] For this, they are expected to have a first line, the shebang line, which names the interpreter executable.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] When the shell tells the kernel to execute the file, it will use the interpreter `/bin/bash`.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] For a script written in another language, just replace `/bin/bash` with the interpreter for that language.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] For example: `/usr/bin/python` for a python script, or `/usr/local/bin/fish` for a fish script, if that is where you have them installed.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] If you want to share your script with others, you might want to use **env** to allow for the interpreter to be installed in other locations.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] This will call `env`, which then goes through `PATH` to find a program called “fish”.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] This makes it work, whether fish is installed in (for example) `/usr/local/bin/fish`, `/usr/bin/fish`, or `~/.local/bin/fish`, as long as that directory is in `PATH`.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] The shebang line is only used when scripts are executed without specifying the interpreter.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] For functions inside fish or when executing a script with `fish /path/to/script`, a shebang is not required (but it doesn’t hurt!).
[src:fish-shell/index-page] When executing files without an interpreter, fish, like other shells, tries your system shell, typically `/bin/sh`.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] This is needed because some scripts are shipped without a shebang line.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] To store configuration write it to a file called `~/.config/fish/config.fish`.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] `.fish` scripts in `~/.config/fish/conf.d/` are also automatically executed before `config.fish`.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] These files are read on the startup of every shell, whether interactive and/or if they’re login shells.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] Use `status --is-interactive` and `status --is-login` to do things only in interactive/login shells, respectively.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] This is the short version; for a full explanation, like for sysadmins or integration for developers of other software, see Configuration files.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] If you want to see what you changed over fish’s defaults, see fish_delta.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] This is just an example; using fish_add_path e.g.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] `fish_add_path ~/linux/bin` which only adds the path if it isn’t included yet is easier.
[src:fish-shell/index-page] If you have an improvement for fish, you can submit it via the GitHub page.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] A **Unix shell** is a shell that provides a command-line user interface for a Unix-like operating system.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] A Unix shell provides a command language that can be used either interactively or for writing a shell script.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] A user typically works within a Unix shell via a terminal emulator; however, direct access via serial hardware connections or a Secure Shell are common for server systems.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] Although use of a Unix shell is popular with some users, others prefer to use a graphical shell in a windowing system, such as those provided in desktop Linux distributions or macOS, instead of a command-line interface (CLI).
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] A user may have access to multiple Unix shells with one configured to run by default when the user logs in interactively.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] The default selection is typically stored in a user's profile (for example, in the local passwd file or in a distributed configuration system such as NIS or LDAP).
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] A user may use other shells nested inside the default shell.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] A Unix shell may provide many features including: variable definition and substitution, command substitution, filename wildcarding, stream piping, control flow structures (condition-testing and iteration), working directory context, and here document.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] The first Unix shell was the Thompson shell, *sh*, written by Ken Thompson at Bell Labs and distributed with Versions 1 through 6 of Unix, from 1971 to 1975.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] Though rudimentary by modern standards, it introduced many of the basic features common to all later Unix shells, including piping, simple control structures using `if` and `goto`, and filename GLOBbing.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] Though not in current use, it is still available as part of some Ancient UNIX systems, such as Version 6 Unix.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] It was modeled after the Multics shell, developed in 1965 by American software engineer Glenda Schroeder.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] Schroeder's Multics shell was itself modeled after the RUNCOM program Louis Pouzin showed to the Multics Team.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] The "rc" suffix on some Unix configuration files (e.g.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] ".bashrc" or ".vimrc"), is a remnant of the RUNCOM ancestry of Unix shells.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] The PWB shell or Mashey shell, *sh*, was an upward-compatible version of the Thompson shell, augmented by John Mashey and others and distributed with the Programmer's Workbench UNIX, circa 1975–1977.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] It focused on making shell programming practical, especially in large shared computing centers.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] It added shell variables (precursors of environment variables, including the search path mechanism that evolved into $PATH), user-executable shell scripts, and interrupt-handling.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] Control structures were extended from if/goto to if/then/else/endif, switch/breaksw/endsw, and while/end/break/continue.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] As shell programming became widespread, these external commands were incorporated into the shell itself for performance.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] But the most widely distributed and influential of the early Unix shells were the Bourne shell and the C shell.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] Both shells have been used as the coding base and model for many derivative and work-alike shells with extended feature sets.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] The Bourne shell, *sh*, was a new Unix shell by Stephen Bourne at Bell Labs.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] Distributed as the shell for UNIX Version 7 in 1979, it introduced the rest of the basic features considered common to all the later Unix shells, including here documents, command substitution, more generic variables and more extensive builtin control structures.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] The language, including the use of a reversed keyword to mark the end of a block, was influenced by ALGOL 68.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] Traditionally, the Bourne shell program name is sh and its path in the Unix file system hierarchy is /bin/sh.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] But a number of compatible work-alikes are also available with various improvements and additional features.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] The POSIX standard specifies its standard shell as a strict subset of the Korn shell.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] From a user's perspective the Bourne shell was immediately recognized when active by its characteristic default command line prompt character, the dollar sign ($).
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] The C shell, *csh*, was modeled on the C programming language, including the control structures and the expression grammar.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] It was written by Bill Joy as a graduate student at University of California, Berkeley, and was widely distributed with BSD Unix.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] The C shell also introduced many features for interactive work, including the history and editing mechanisms, aliases, directory stacks, tilde notation, cdpath, job control and path hashing.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] On many systems, csh may be a symbolic link or hard link to TENEX C shell (tcsh), an improved version of Joy's original version.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] Although the interactive features of csh have been copied to most other shells, the language structure has not been widely copied.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] The only work-alike is Hamilton C shell, written by Nicole Hamilton, first distributed on OS/2 in 1988 and on Windows since 1992.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] Shells read configuration files in various circumstances.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] These files usually contain commands for the shell and are executed when loaded; they are usually used to set important variables used to find executables, like $PATH, and others that control the behavior and appearance of the shell.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] The table in this section shows the configuration files for popular shells.
[src:fish-shell/unix-shell] Same behavior as sh, but only if invoked as sh (bash 2+) or, since bash 4.2, also if invoked *explicitly* in POSIX compatibility mode (with options --posix or -o posix).
